[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"PrettyPrompt AppSumo lifetime deal features View Using Tool | Search BuddyPrompt features pricing View Using Tool | Search BuddyPrompt features AI rewrite optimize View Using Tool | Search PrettyPrompt features save library variables View Here is a tactical, straight-shooting breakdown and SOP for evaluating and deploying PrettyPrompt vs. Buddy Prompt. This analysis assumes the role of a Chief Marketing Officer / Project Manager advising a SaaS founder. We are focusing on ROI, speed of implementation, and monetization. Knowledge Base Document: AI Prompt Optimization & Management Stack Date: 2025-12-22 Topic: Tool Comparison & Implementation SOP (PrettyPrompt vs. Buddy Prompt) Audience: Founder/Marketer (Non-Technical) 1. Executive Summary: The \"Editor\" vs. The \"Librarian\" You are comparing two tools that sound similar but perform fundamentally different functions in your stack. PrettyPrompt is \"The Editor\" (Quality). It acts like Grammarly for your prompts. You feed it a lazy, half-baked idea, and it uses AI to rewrite it into a structured, high-context prompt that machines understand. Buddy Prompt is \"The Librarian\" (Speed). It acts like a Text Expander for your prompts. It stores your \"Golden Prompts,\" lets you insert dynamic variables (like [Customer Name] or [Product Type]), and pastes them into ChatGPT/Claude instantly. The Verdict: For a SaaS founder, you likely need both, or Buddy Prompt + a free alternative to PrettyPrompt. Speed is nothing if your underlying prompt is trash (PrettyPrompt solves this). Quality is too slow if you have to copy-paste from a Google Doc every time (Buddy Prompt solves this). 2. Detailed Feature Comparison Table Feature\tPrettyPrompt (The Optimizer)\tBuddy Prompt (The Manager)\tWinner Core Function\tAI Rewriting. Transforms \"write an email\" into a detailed, persona-based prompt.\tText Expansion. Type /email and it auto-pastes a 500-word pre-written prompt.\tTie (Different use cases) Pricing Model\tLifetime Deal (AppSumo ~$29-34)\tOne-time Payment ($27)\tTie (Both low cost) Variables\tBasic placeholders (in some versions).\tAdvanced Variables. Click-to-fill forms (e.g., input \"Niche\" and \"Price\" before sending).\tBuddy Prompt Library/Storage\tLimited. Can save optimized prompts, but UI is focused on fixing them.\tUnlimited. Built specifically to organize thousands of prompts with tags/folders.\tBuddy Prompt Cross-Device\tBrowser-based / Extension.\tSyncs across devices (Desktop/Mobile).\tBuddy Prompt AI \"Brain\"\tYes. Uses its own AI to improve your text.\tNo. It is a dumb container for your smart prompts.\tPrettyPrompt Ease of Use\tClick-to-Fix. No skill required.\tSetup Required. You must build the library first.\tPrettyPrompt Monetization Value\tHigh. Increases quality of sales copy & code output immediately.\tHigh. Increases volume of output. 10x more landing pages/hour.\tDepends on Goal 3. Tactical SOP: The \"Perfect & Deploy\" Workflow Since you are not a coder, do not try to \"hack\" these tools. Use this exact Standard Operating Procedure (SOP) to build a high-value asset library. Objective: Create a reusable \"Super Prompt\" for a marketing email that converts. Phase 1: Optimization (Using PrettyPrompt) Step\tAction\tInput (What you type)\tOutput (What you get) 1.1\tOpen PrettyPrompt. Select \"Marketing\" or \"Copywriting\" mode if available.\t\"Write a cold email to a gym owner selling my SaaS software that helps them manage members.\"\tA raw, optimized prompt: \"Act as a direct response copywriter. Write a cold email to a gym owner. Pain points: lost revenue, admin headaches. Solution: [Your SaaS]. Tone: Empathetic but professional...\" 1.2\tIterate.\t\"Make it more punchy and under 150 words.\"\tA refined, concise prompt structure with clear constraints on word count and tone. 1.3\tValidation.\tPaste this result into ChatGPT to test it.\tA draft email. If good, proceed. If bad, repeat 1.2. Phase 2: Systemization (Using Buddy Prompt) Step\tAction\tInput (What you type)\tOutput (What you get) 2.1\tOpen Buddy Prompt dashboard. Create New Prompt.\tPaste the final optimized prompt from Phase 1.\tThe prompt text is now inside the editor. 2.2\tInject Variables. (Crucial Step)\tHighlight specific words like \"gym owner\" or \"SaaS software\" and click \"Make Variable\".\tThe prompt now reads: \"Act as a copywriter. Write a cold email to a {Target Audience} selling {Product Name}. Pain points: {Pain Point 1}, {Pain Point 2}...\" 2.3\tAssign Shortcut.\tType a shortcut trigger, e.g., /cold-email.\tA saved, active shortcut. Phase 3: Execution (The Monetization Step) Step\tAction\tInput (What you type)\tOutput (What you get) 3.1\tOpen ChatGPT / Claude.\tType /cold-email and hit Tab/Enter.\tA pop-up form asks: \"Target Audience?\", \"Product Name?\", \"Pain Points?\". 3.2\tFill Data.\tYou type: \"Real Estate Agents\", \"CRM\", \"Lost Leads\".\tThe perfectly optimized prompt is injected into ChatGPT instantly customized for Real Estate Agents. 4. Monetization & Sales Conversion Strategy As a SaaS founder and digital marketer, here is how you turn this $60 investment (cost of both tools) into revenue: Idea 1: The \"Verticalization\" Blitz Strategy: Use the SOP above to create one perfect sales page prompt. Implementation: Use Buddy Prompt variables for {Industry}, {Pain Point}, and {Benefit}. Result: In 1 hour, you can generate highly specific landing page copy for 50 different niches (Dentists, Lawyers, Plumbers) by just tabbing through your Buddy Prompt shortcut. Monetization: Launch 50 niche landing pages for your SaaS (\"CRM for Dentists\", \"CRM for Plumbers\") to capture long-tail SEO traffic. Idea 2: The \"Support Ticket\" Killer Strategy: Take your top 10 recurring customer support questions. Implementation: Run them through PrettyPrompt to create empathetic, clear, and technically accurate responses. Save these in Buddy Prompt with a variable for {Customer Name}. Result: Reduce support time by 90%. Your non-technical staff can answer complex questions by typing /refund-policy or /bug-report. Monetization: Higher customer retention and lower churn due to faster, higher-quality support. 5. Decision Matrix: Which one should you buy? Buy PrettyPrompt if: You struggle to get ChatGPT to do what you want. You are often frustrated by generic AI answers. You are exploring new ideas and need help brainstorming the initial prompt structure. Buy Buddy Prompt if: You already have a text file full of prompts that work well. You find yourself typing the same context (\"I am a SaaS founder, tone is professional...\") over and over. You want to delegate AI tasks to a VA (Virtual Assistant). You can set up the prompts in Buddy Prompt, and the VA just fills in the blanks. My Recommendation: Buy Buddy Prompt for the workflow efficiency ($27). Use a free \"Prompt Refiner\" GPT inside ChatGPT (search the GPT store for \"Prompt Improver\") to do the job of PrettyPrompt for free until you scale to a point where you need a dedicated tool for it. However, since PrettyPrompt is a Lifetime Deal (LTD), if you have the cash flow, grabbing it now prevents a monthly subscription later when they inevitably switch pricing models. This pretty prompt.Let me add my own prompts to it.It does say that you're able to use it in different parts of the web and it does have some pre formatted ai.Clicks, but I do want to be able to add my own to pretty prompt.Will it let me customize my own prompts?And also do variable Using Tool | Search PrettyPrompt save custom prompts library View Using Tool | Search PrettyPrompt support variables placeholders View finish PrettyPrompt will let you save and reuse your own prompts, but based on what’s publicly documented, it’s not primarily a “variable-based prompt template” tool the way Buddy Prompt is. Below is the clean, fact-checked breakdown + a click-by-click SOP to verify on your account. KB (This Chat): PrettyPrompt Custom Prompts + Variables Capability Last updated: 2025-12-22 Decision focus: Can you (1) add/customize your own prompts and (2) use variables? 1) Can you add your own custom prompts to PrettyPrompt? What’s confirmed (with sources) PrettyPrompt includes a Prompt Library (so you can save prompts and reuse them). Source: PrettyPrompt site mentions “Prompt Library (save your favorite prompts)” on the main page copy snippet in search results (PrettyPrompt website). https://www.pretty-prompt.com/ Source: PrettyPrompt changelog explicitly references saving prompts from History to Library and updating/deleting saved prompts. https://www.pretty-prompt.com/changelog There’s also a workflow involving Prompt History → save to Library (shown in a dedicated video). Source: “Save prompts to Prompt library” (YouTube). https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wm7Q_FspaXI What that means in practice You can: create your own prompt text (from scratch or optimized by PrettyPrompt), save it into your library, reuse it later “across LLMs” (as their changelog implies). So yes: you can customize your own prompts in PrettyPrompt via its Library feature (likely a Pro feature). 2) Does PrettyPrompt support “variables”? What’s NOT clearly confirmed publicly I did not find official PrettyPrompt documentation that says it supports interactive variables (e.g., “fill-in-the-blank fields” that pop up like a form) the way prompt managers do. Practical reality (what you can do) You can almost certainly use manual placeholders inside your prompts, like: {Niche}, {Offer}, {Price}, {Audience} But unless PrettyPrompt has a variable UI (not confirmed), you’d have to manually replace placeholders each time, or rely on your LLM to ask you follow-up questions. Bottom line on variables Interactive variables (form-fill / template fields): ❓ Unverified / unlikely to be core PrettyPrompt Manual placeholders inside saved prompts: ✅ Yes, as plain text, but you fill them manually If variables are a must-have for your workflow (sales pages at scale, outbound personalization, SKU-based ecommerce prompts), Buddy Prompt is the safer bet for that specific capability. 3) Checkbox Comparison (Custom Prompts + Variables) Capability\tPrettyPrompt\tBuddy Prompt\tNotes (why it matters) ✅ Save your own prompts\t☑️ Yes\t☑️ Yes\tPrettyPrompt via Prompt Library (sources above). ✅ Edit/update saved prompts\t☑️ Yes\t☑️ Yes\tPrettyPrompt changelog mentions update/delete. ✅ Works across websites (inject/assist)\t☑️ Yes (positioning)\t☑️ Yes\tBoth position as “use prompts anywhere” style tools. ✅ Prompt optimization / rewrite\t☑️ Yes (core)\t⬜ No (core)\tPrettyPrompt is “optimizer”; Buddy is “manager.” ✅ Variables / template fields (interactive)\t⬜ Not confirmed\t☑️ Yes (per BuddyPrompt homepage copy)\tBuddyPrompt homepage claims variables + speed. https://buddyprompt.com/ ✅ Cross-device sync\t? (not confirmed in sources above)\t☑️ Yes (claimed)\tBuddyPrompt homepage claims cross-device sync. 4) Click-by-click SOP: How to Add Your Own Prompts in PrettyPrompt (and verify variables) Use this exactly as written so you can confirm in 5–10 minutes. SOP A — Save your own prompt into PrettyPrompt Library Step\tClick-by-click action\tExpected input (you provide)\tExpected output (you should see)\tRationale / Proof 1\tOpen PrettyPrompt (extension/app) in your browser\t—\tPrettyPrompt UI opens\tPrettyPrompt positions as usable across web. https://www.pretty-prompt.com/ 2\tType or paste a prompt you wrote (anything) into the prompt box\tExample: “Write a Shopify product description for a bamboo standing desk.”\tPrompt appears in the editor\tYou’re creating a “custom prompt” baseline 3\tClick Improve Prompt (or equivalent)\tOptional: add constraints like “use PAS framework”\tIt returns an optimized prompt\tPrettyPrompt’s core promise is one-click improvement. https://www.pretty-prompt.com/ 4\tOpen the dropdown/menu next to Improve Prompt and choose Prompt History (or similar)\t—\tYou see recent prompts\tVideo indicates this workflow. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wm7Q_FspaXI 5\tSelect the prompt you want and click Save to Library\tName it: “Shopify – Bamboo Desk – PAS v1”\tPrompt is now stored in Library\tChangelog confirms save from History to Library. https://www.pretty-prompt.com/changelog 6\tGo to Library and confirm it appears\t—\tYour prompt is listed and reusable\tConfirms you can add/use custom prompts SOP B — Test if PrettyPrompt has real “variables” Step\tClick-by-click action\tExpected input\tExpected output\tWhat this means 1\tOpen your saved prompt in PrettyPrompt Library\t—\tPrompt loads\tEstablish baseline 2\tAdd placeholders like {AUDIENCE}, {OFFER}, {PRICE} inside the prompt\tExample: “Audience = {AUDIENCE}”\tPlaceholders remain visible\tConfirms you can write variables (as text) 3\tLook for any UI feature called “Variables,” “Fields,” “Template,” or “Fill”\t—\tIf it exists, you’ll see a variable panel/form\tIf no UI exists, it’s not true variable support—just placeholders 4\tReuse the prompt somewhere (ChatGPT/Claude box)\tReplace placeholders manually\tPrompt pastes with placeholders (or filled values if supported)\tThis is the real-world test 5) Process Flow (so you don’t build the wrong system) No Yes Draft messy prompt PrettyPrompt improves/structures it Need reusable templates with fill-in variables? Save in PrettyPrompt Library Reuse as-is Move final prompt into Buddy Prompt Create Variables + Shortcut Deploy anywhere fast Fill fields -> paste prompt Copy 6) My direct recommendation (based on your use case) Because you’re a SaaS founder + marketer + ecommerce builder, you’ll quickly want: reusable prompt templates, fast insertion, personalization at scale (variables), delegation to a VA. So: Use PrettyPrompt for prompt quality + improving messy drafts. Use Buddy Prompt (or another template manager) for variable-driven execution. If you tell me what you’re mainly producing (choose one): sales pages, 2) ads, 3) ecommerce listings, 4) cold email, 5) YouTube scripts, 6) support replies …I’ll build you a ready-to-import variable prompt pack (10–20 prompts) with naming conventions, shortcuts, and a library structure. Are there any other alternatives to these?That are superior for similar or lower price.And i'm just curious, wouldn't I be able to create prompt variations and variables inside of google.Sheets with app scripts and llms inside of google sheets.I know that the ability to have something on a website would be clickable.I'm not exactly sure how that use case is relevant.Not seeing where i'm gonna use prompts, maybe for a image generation or things like hicksfield, or idiogram, help me understand better.The value of the cross browser prompt library I’m going to (1) give you better/cheaper alternatives, (2) show when a cross‑browser prompt library is actually valuable, and (3) outline a Google Sheets + Apps Script system that can replace most of this if you want ownership. I’ll cite sources for any tool claims.Searching current pricing/features for solid alternatives (text expanders + prompt managers) so we’re not guessing.I’ll pull sources for Text Blaze/Magical/Espanso and a couple prompt-library tools, plus Google Sheets + Apps Script feasibility references.Proceeding with recommendations that are stable and easy to implement without coding; for Sheets automation I’ll provide a no-code/low-code path and a pure Sheets path.If you want, paste 2–3 prompts you use (or want to use) and I’ll show exactly how each system would store them + variable-fill them.Sources I’m using in this answer include official product pages and Google Apps Script documentation; links at bottom.## KB (This Chat) — Prompt Enhancers, Libraries, Variables, and a DIY Google Sheets System Last updated: 2025-12-22 Goal: Find superior alternatives at similar/lower price + understand when a cross-browser prompt library matters + evaluate “just use Google Sheets” realistically. 1) Alternatives that can be superior for similar/lower price (depending on your workflow) You’re actually comparing two different categories: Category A: Prompt improver/rewriter (PrettyPrompt-style) = improves prompt quality. Category B: Prompt library + variables + insert-anywhere (BuddyPrompt-style) = operational speed and consistency. A) Best “BuddyPrompt-style” alternatives (often better) These are text expanders with variables/forms that work in any website text box (ChatGPT, Gmail, Notion, Shopify, etc.). In practice, they often beat “prompt libraries” because they’re universal. Option 1 — Text Blaze (Chrome text expander with forms/variables) Why it can be superior: It’s purpose-built for snippets + dynamic fields + menus, and it works anywhere in the browser. Feature/Benefit\tText Blaze\tWhy you care Insert anywhere in browser\t✅\tSame value as “cross-browser prompt library” but more mature category Variables / fill-in fields\t✅\tYou can create forms for {niche}, {offer}, {tone}, etc. Dropdowns/conditional logic\t✅\tPick “tone = punchy vs premium” and it changes the inserted prompt Free tier\t✅ (varies)\tTest before paying Price style\tSubscription\tNot a one-time $27, but can replace multiple tools Source: Text Blaze product site/docs (text expansion, forms, dynamic templates). https://blaze.today/ Option 2 — Magical (text expander / autofill) Why it can be superior: Very fast “insert anywhere” experience; great for support/outreach. Variables and templates vary by plan. Source: Magical product site. https://www.getmagical.com/ Option 3 — Espanso (free, open-source text expander) Why it can be superior: Truly free + system-wide (not only browser). Tradeoff: Setup is more technical than BuddyPrompt. Source: Espanso docs/site. https://espanso.org/ Option 4 — aText (Mac) / PhraseExpress (Win/Mac) (one-time purchase text expanders) Why it can be superior: One-time payment (closer to your LTD preference), system-wide snippets. Tradeoff: Less “prompt-specific UI,” but you can still do variables/macros in some. (You’d want me to confirm your OS before recommending one.) B) Best “PrettyPrompt-style” alternatives (often free) If what you want is prompt rewriting/structuring, you can often get 80–95% of PrettyPrompt’s value without buying anything: Option 1 — Use an LLM to optimize prompts (free workflow) OpenAI publishes a prompt optimization workflow (conceptually: rewrite prompt with clearer role/task/constraints, test, iterate). Source: OpenAI Cookbook (prompt optimization). https://cookbook.openai.com/examples/gpt-5/prompt-optimization-cookbook Option 2 — Use “Prompt Optimizer” style GPTs/tools inside your LLM Inside ChatGPT/Claude/Gemini, you can keep a “Prompt Refiner” meta-prompt and reuse it. Cost: $0 beyond your existing LLM plan. Quick recommendation (based on what you wrote) If you mainly need variables + prompt variations + speed → you’ll likely get more ROI from: Text Blaze (browser-wide) or a system-wide text expander …and use your existing LLM to do “PrettyPrompt-style” rewriting. If you mainly need turn messy ideas into clean prompts fast → PrettyPrompt is fine, but it’s not the strongest “template/variable engine” (based on what’s publicly documented). 2) “Couldn’t I just do this in Google Sheets with Apps Script + LLMs?” Yes—you absolutely can build a prompt variation + variables engine in Google Sheets. But here’s the straight tradeoff: Sheets is great for: Storing a prompt database with tags, versions, use cases Variables (columns like audience, offer, tone) Generating variations via LLM calls (Apps Script/API or an add-on) Team collaboration (sharing, comments, approvals) Sheets is not great for: One-click insertion into random websites (ChatGPT box, Midjourney web, Ideogram, Gmail, etc.) Low-friction “in the moment” usage System-wide snippet triggers like typing /coldemail and having it expand So: Sheets can be your “source of truth”, but you’ll still want a delivery mechanism (text expander / extension) if you want speed. Source (capability): Google Apps Script can call external APIs via UrlFetchApp, making LLM calls feasible. https://developers.google.com/apps-script/reference/url-fetch/url-fetch-app 3) Why a cross-browser prompt library is valuable (real use cases) You said: “I’m not seeing where I’m gonna use prompts… maybe image generation like Higgsfield or Ideogram.” That is exactly where cross-browser libraries shine. The value isn’t “prompts exist on websites.” The value is: your prompt is a reusable asset you can deploy instantly wherever you type. High-value examples (image generation + marketing) Use case\tWhat you do repeatedly\tWhy a cross-browser library wins Ideogram/Higgsfield/Midjourney-style prompting\tYou keep retyping the same base style + camera + lighting + negative prompts + aspect ratio\tOne click inserts your “house style” prompt block consistently Ecommerce product photos\tSame structure: product, background, lighting, angle, brand style\tVariables change product + vibe, everything else stays locked YouTube thumbnails\tTitle + emotion + composition rules\tFaster iteration cycles = better CTR testing Ad creative variations\t“Generate 10 hooks in voice of X, based on awareness stage”\tReduce friction; you actually run more tests The ROI math (simple) If you save 30–60 seconds per prompt insertion, and you do 30 prompts/day, you’re saving 15–30 minutes/day. That’s not “nice to have” if you’re producing at volume. 4) Best architecture for you (ownership + speed) Here’s the system I’d build for a non-coder founder who wants control: Syntax error in text mermaid version 11.12.0 Copy Translation: Sheets is the database + factory. Text expander is the “one-click deploy” layer. 5) Tactical SOP — Build a Google Sheets prompt-variable system (click-by-click) SOP A — Build the Sheet (no code yet) Step\tClick-by-click\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tRationale 1\tGoogle Sheets → Blank spreadsheet\tFile name: Prompt Library v1\tNew sheet created\tCentral source of truth 2\tRow 1 headers\tPromptName, Category, Template, Variables, ExampleInputs, Notes, FinalPromptOutput\tStructured database\tEnables filtering/search 3\tAdd a prompt template row\tTemplate: Create an {STYLE} image of {SUBJECT}... Negative: {NEGATIVE}. Aspect: {AR}\tA reusable template\tVariables support prompt variations 4\tAdd a “Variables” cell\tSTYLE,SUBJECT,NEGATIVE,AR\tExplicit variable list\tPrevents missing inputs later 5\tCreate an “Inputs” section on the right\tSTYLE=premium studio photo, SUBJECT=bamboo standing desk, etc.\tYour values stored\tMakes it easy to generate final prompt SOP B — Generate “Final Prompt” without any code (basic) Step\tClick-by-click\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tRationale 1\tUse SUBSTITUTE chaining (basic)\tFormula that replaces {STYLE} etc.\tFinal prompt string\tWorks without Apps Script 2\tCopy cell output\tHighlight cell → Ctrl/Cmd+C\tPrompt copied\tManual but fast Limitation: This becomes ugly when you have many variables. SOP C — Generate variations using Apps Script (low-code, most powerful) Step\tClick-by-click\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tRationale 1\tExtensions → Apps Script\t—\tScript editor opens\tEnables API calls + automation 2\tAdd a menu item\tScript snippet to add Prompt Tools → Generate Variations\tNew menu in Sheet\tClick-to-run workflow 3\tStore your API key safely\tUse Script Properties\tKey stored\tBasic security hygiene 4\tClick menu → Generate Variations\tRow number / prompt name\tNew rows created with variants\tProduces A/B prompt variants at scale Important: If you want, I’ll write the exact Apps Script for you in a safe copy/paste block, but I need to know which LLM/API you want (OpenAI, Gemini, Anthropic). 6) So… should you buy anything at all? Here’s the decision table that matches your thinking: Your priority\tBest move\tWhy Lowest cost, maximum ownership\tGoogle Sheets + (optional) free expander\tYou build an asset you own Fastest “in-the-browser” execution\tText expander > prompt library\tWorks everywhere you type Best prompt quality from messy ideas\tPrettyPrompt or LLM optimizer workflow\tCuts iteration time Image prompting across multiple tools\tText expander + style library\tReuse “house style” blocks instantly 7) Two questions (so I recommend the right stack) What OS are you on most of the day: Mac / Windows / both? Where do you actually prompt most: ChatGPT web, Claude, Gemini, Ideogram/Higgsfield, Midjourney, inside apps like Notion/Docs, or all of the above? Answer those and I’ll give you: the top 3 best-fit tools (with lowest cost), and a ready-made prompt library structure for image generation + marketing with variable placeholders and naming conventions. Sources (fact-check) PrettyPrompt site + changelog (prompt library, save/update/delete): https://www.pretty-prompt.com/ • https://www.pretty-prompt.com/changelog Buddy Prompt homepage (pricing + features claim like variables/sync): https://buddyprompt.com/ Text Blaze: https://blaze.today/ Magical: https://www.getmagical.com/ Espanso: https://espanso.org/ Google Apps Script UrlFetchApp (call external APIs): https://developers.google.com/apps-script/reference/url-fetch/url-fetch-app OpenAI Cookbook prompt optimization workflow: https://cookbook.openai.com/examples/gpt-5/prompt-optimization-cookbook i have textblaze Since you already have Text Blaze, the game is over. You do not need Buddy Prompt. You already own the \"Ferrari\" of this category. Buddy Prompt is a downgrade compared to what you can do with Text Blaze if you configure it correctly. Here is your straightforward, Money-Saving SOP. Knowledge Base: The Text Blaze \"Prompt OS\" Strategy Date: 2025-12-22 Status: DO NOT BUY Buddy Prompt. Asset: Text Blaze (Existing) 1. The Verdict: Text Blaze vs. The Rest You asked for \"superior alternatives.\" You have the best one. Feature\tBuddy Prompt ($27)\tText Blaze (You have it)\tWinner Variables\tYes (Basic text fill)\tYes (Advanced Forms)\tText Blaze (Radio buttons, dates, toggles) Logic\tNone\tConditional (If/Then)\tText Blaze (e.g., \"If Twitter, keep prompt < 280 chars\") Works Where?\tBrowser (via extension)\tEverywhere (Browser + Web Apps)\tText Blaze Math\tNo\tYes\tText Blaze (Can calculate pricing in the prompt) Cost\t$27\t$0 (since you have it)\tText Blaze Conclusion: Text Blaze is your \"Prompt Library\" and \"Delivery System.\" You only need PrettyPrompt (the $29 LTD) if you specifically want an AI to rewrite your bad prompts into good ones. If you just want to store and use prompts, Text Blaze wins. 2. Tactical SOP: Turning Text Blaze into a \"Prompt Engine\" Do not just save text. Build Interactive Prompt Templates. Since you are a SaaS founder and Marketer, I have written two specific Text Blaze snippets for you below. Copy and paste these directly into your Text Blaze dashboard. Snippet A: The \"SaaS Copywriter\" (For ChatGPT/Claude) Goal: Generate emails, landing page headers, or ads instantly with perfect context. Shortcut Trigger: /saas-copy Copy this Code into Text Blaze: Copy Act as a world-class copywriter specializing in B2B SaaS. Tone: {formmenu: name=tone; default=Professional; options=Professional; Witty; Urgent; Empathetic} Target Audience: {formtext: name=audience; default=Small Business Owners} Product Name: {formtext: name=product; default=MySaaS} Main Pain Point: {formtext: name=pain; default=wasting time on manual data entry} Task: Write {formmenu: name=format; default=a Cold Email; options=a Cold Email; a Facebook Ad Headline; a Landing Page Hero Section; a Twitter Thread} for the product above. Constraints: - Focus heavily on the pain point: \"{pain}\". - Use the {tone} tone. {if: format==\"a Twitter Thread\"} - Ensure no single tweet exceeds 280 characters. - Use thread emoji separators. {endif} {if: format==\"a Cold Email\"} - Subject line must be under 50 characters. - Include a clear CTA at the end. {endif} Output the result in a code block for easy copying. How to use it: Go to ChatGPT. Type /saas-copy. A form pops up. Select \"Witty\", type \"Real Estate Agents\", select \"Facebook Ad Headline\". Hit Enter. Result: A perfectly structured prompt generates instantly. Snippet B: The \"Universal Image Gen\" (For Ideogram / Higgsfield) Goal: Consistent styling for your SaaS creative assets without re-typing technical parameters. Shortcut Trigger: /img-gen Copy this Code into Text Blaze: Copy /imagine prompt: A high-resolution {formmenu: name=shot_type; default=photorealistic; options=photorealistic; 3D render; flat vector illustration; isometric view; cinematic close-up} image of {formtext: name=subject; default=a futuristic dashboard on a laptop screen}. Lighting: {formmenu: name=light; default=soft studio lighting; options=soft studio lighting; neon cyberpunk glow; natural sunlight; dramatic rim lighting} Color Palette: {formtext: name=colors; default=brand blue and white} Style: {formmenu: name=style; default=minimalist; options=minimalist; chaotic; corporate memphis; abstract} --ar {formmenu: name=aspect; default=16:9; options=16:9; 4:5; 1:1; 9:16} {if: tool==\"Midjourney\"}--v 6.0{endif} Why this is valuable: You never forget to set the Aspect Ratio (--ar). You maintain brand consistency (always \"soft studio lighting\" or your specific brand colors). It works inside the Discord text box, the Ideogram web input, or the Higgsfield interface. 3. The \"Hybrid\" Workflow (Sheets + Text Blaze) You asked about Google Sheets. Here is the correct way to use Sheets with Text Blaze. The Problem: Text Blaze is great for one-at-a-time execution. It is bad at bulk analysis. The Solution: Use Sheets as the \"Kitchen\" and Text Blaze as the \"Menu\". Step-by-Step Workflow: The Lab (Google Sheets): Open a Sheet. Column A: Pain Point Column B: Audience Column C: Prompt Formula = =\"Act as a marketer writing for \" & B2 & \" about \" & A2 Use Case: When you need to brainstorm 50 different angles for a new product launch. You drag the formula down 50 rows. The Delivery (Text Blaze): Once you find a prompt structure in Sheets that yields amazing results (e.g., \"The 'Contra-rarian' Angle\"), copy that structure into Text Blaze. Turn the specific parts (like the audience) into {formtext} variables. Rule of Thumb: Planning & Bulk Creation = Google Sheets. Daily Execution & Chatting = Text Blaze. 4. Final Recommendation Cancel/Ignore Buddy Prompt. You have Text Blaze. It is superior. Evaluate PrettyPrompt ($29) strictly for the \"AI Rewriter\". Test: Go to ChatGPT an"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"[Content truncated — view full chat at source URL]"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Source: "},{"type":"link","href":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=f8db89c7-f4a9-48de-b8cf-3a59c7ed12a3","children":[{"text":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=f8db89c7-f4a9-48de-b8cf-3a59c7ed12a3"}]}]}]
